}

Core rules
- Remain strictly faithful. Include only facts and artifacts present in the input. Do not invent or extrapolate.
- Omit missing information. Do not write placeholders like "Not provided in input."
- ASCII only. No emojis or non-ASCII symbols.
- Inline-cite any URLs that appear in the input using [label](url). Never invent links or titles.
- Keep wording short and skimmable. Prefer bullets and short phrases over long sentences.

Structure
- Root node: summarize the main topic. label <= 6 words. description up to 30 words.
- Depth: target 2 to 4 levels total (root is level 1).
- Branching: each node typically has 2 to 5 subthemes. Merge or split to stay within this range.
- Total size: keep compact, aim for <= 25 nodes overall.
- One idea per label. If a label needs "and" or commas, split it.
- Sibling subthemes are MECE (mutually exclusive and collectively exhaustive) for their parent.

Fusion vs. granularity
- Top and mid levels: aggressively merge related ideas to produce fewer, stronger categories. Summarize here.
- Leaf level: do not summarize further. State concrete details exactly as in the input (definitions, conditions, steps, examples, data).

Descriptions
- Root and main subthemes: brief paragraph or tight bullet list that synthesizes the input segment.
- Leaf nodes: crisp statements or artifacts strictly from the input.
- When artifacts exist in the input, include a concise snippet:
  - Coding: short fenced code block from the input (```...```), minimal comments.
  - Math/Proof: compact LaTeX equation or ordered proof steps from the input.
  - Data/CLI: key command or query from the input.
  - Science/Engineering: formula or tiny table from the input.
- Do not fabricate code, proofs, formulas, metrics, examples, or numbers.

Compression and naming
- De-duplicate overlaps; keep the clearest version.
- Prefer precise terms and symbols over prose.
- Use canonical labels; handle synonyms in the description if needed.
- Keep a consistent label style: noun-first ("Gradient descent") or verb-first ("Tune learning rate"); avoid full sentences in labels.

Return only the Theme JSON object and nothing else.